{{BLP sources| date= May 2018}} {{Infobox Muslim scholar |honorific_prefix = |name = Ḥassan al-Kettani |image = |caption = |title = [[Sheikh]] |birth_name = Ḥassan al-Kettani |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |death_cause = |resting_place = |other_names = |nationality = [[Moroccan people|Moroccan]] |ethnicity = [[Arabs|Arab]] |era = |region = |occupation = |denomination = [[Sunni]] |jurisprudence = |creed = [[Athari]] |movement = [[Salafi]] |main_interests = |notable_ideas = |notable_works = |alma_mater = |Sufi_order = |disciple_of = |awards = |influences = [[Muhammad Abu Khubza]], [[Abdul Qader Arnaoot]], [[Abdullah al-Ghumari]], [[Abd al-Aziz al-Ghumari]] |influenced = [[Salafia Jihadia]] |module = |website = }} '''Ḥassan al-Kettani''' ({{lang-ar|حسن الكتاني}}; born 16 August 1972 in [[Salé]]) is a Muslim preacher and former political prisoner from Morocco. He was imprisoned for alleged connections to the [[2003 Casablanca bombings]], Kettani was pardoned by [[Mohammed VI]] eight years later after efforts by his lawyer, human rights groups and Islamists success in Morocco's parliament.
==Personal life== The Kettani family has historically been a part of Morocco's religious establishment, serving as both academics and preachers for centuries. He is the great grandson of [[Muḥammad ibn Jaʿfar al-Kattānī]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kKHIbdaqeTo</ref> Kettani was as student of fellow Moroccan cleric [[Muhammad Abu Khubza]] in addition to [[Abdullah al-Ghumari]] and [[Abd al-Aziz al-Ghumari]], as well as Albanian cleric [[Abdul Qader Arnaoot]].<ref name=cord>[http://www.cordobaacademy.com/about/faculty Cordoba Academy Faculty] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126062931/http://cordobaacademy.com/about/faculty |date=2013-01-26 }}, © 2012 Cordoba Academy. Accessed February 17, 2013.</ref> His family descends from the Islamic [[Prophets in Islam|prophet]] [[Muhammad]]'s grandson, [[Hasan ibn Ali]].{{Citation needed|date= May 2018}}
==Sentencing== On February 18, 2003, Kettani was arrested by Moroccan authorities.<ref name=pushing>Ilhem Rachidi, [http://www.atimes/atimes/Front_Page/GG01Aa01.html Pushing Islam to the extremes] at [[Asia Times Online]]. July 1, 2005.</ref> On September 23, he was sentenced to 20 years in prison in connection with the [[2003 Casablanca bombings]], for which authorities accused him of being an ideological leader. Kettani denied this and asserted that his conviction was politically motivated and illegal. Human rights groups criticized his sentencing as unfair.<ref name=reflect>Mohamed Saadouni, [http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2012/06/12/feature-02 Moroccan cheikhs reflect on Tunisia deportation] for Magharebia. June 12, 2012.</ref><ref name=euro>Naoufel Cherkaoui, [http://www.eurasiareview.com/28022012-morocco-royal-pardon-marks-new-approach-to-salafi-issue/ Royal Pardon Marks New Approach To Salafi Issue] at the Eurasia Review. February 28, 2012.</ref> In June 2005, he and 664 other Islamists began a hunger strike in prison to protest their convictions.<ref name=pushing/> Moroccan politician [[Mohamed Bouzoubaa]] criticized the move as being more concerned with politics than human rights, though Kettani's lawyer [[Mustafa Ramid]] upheld that he and other Islamists were victims of unjust trials. A second hunger strike took place at the prison in [[Kenitra]] in 2010 though most detainees ceased after negotiations with authorities; Kettani continued the strike longer than all other detainees, continuing to uphold his innocence and demand a reopening of his case.<ref>Mawassi Lahcen, [http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2010/01/06/feature-01 Casablanca prisoners end hunger strike] for Magharebia. June 1, 2010.</ref>
On February 5, 2012, [[Mohammed VI of Morocco]] pardoned Kettani along with other Islamists whom human rights groups believed had been unfairly jailed.<ref>[http://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2012/02/26006/morocco-king-pardons-jailed-islamist-leaders/ Morocco king pardons jailed Islamist leaders] at Morocco World News. [[Reuters]] reporting in [[Rabat]], February 5th, 2012.</ref> Kettani's lawyer Ramid, who later became Morocco's Minister of Justice, referred to the pardon as an attempt by the government to hold out the olive branch for Islamists willing to make positive contributions to public life and shun extremism, comments with which Kettani concurred.<ref name=euro/><ref name=recon>Mohamed Saadouni, [http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/reportage/2012/05/18/reportage-01 Morocco pursues salafist reconciliation] for Magharebia. May 18, 2012.</ref>
==Post-release== Since his pardon, Kettani has denounced extremism and encouraged its rejection among Moroccan conservatives; regardless, he and another Islamist were deported upon arrival at [[Tunis–Carthage International Airport]] on May 14, 2012.<ref name=reflect/><ref name=recon/> Kettani, who had been invited to the country by Tunisian Islamists, claimed he was under the impression that he would be able to enter [[Tunisia]] freely after the [[Tunisian revolution]].<ref>Houda Trabelsi, [http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2012/05/18/feature-01 Tunisia denies entry to Moroccan salafists] by Magharebia. May 18, 2012.</ref> Despite his deportation, Kettani still praised the Tunisian airport security, claiming that he had been treated well by the authorities and even received an apology from [[Ennahda Movement]] officials before his deportation.<ref name=reflect/>
==Views== Kettani has been described as an ideological leader of the [[Salafia Jihadia]] movement, though he and other detainees rejected this and saw themselves as normal Sunni Muslims with a Salafist orientation.<ref name=james>Alison Pargeter, [http://www.jamestown.org/programs/gta/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=483&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=180&no_cache=1 The Islamist Movement in Morocco]. [[The Jamestown Foundation]], May 23, 2005.</ref> Since his pardon he has openly criticized what he defines as [[Wahhabism]], comments which have caused rifts among Moroccan Salafists. He has often spoken against what he sees as depraved Western influence in Moroccan society, and his views prior to his incarceration had been regarded as extreme by many in the security establishment.<ref name=pushing/><ref name=james/> Since his release, Kettani and several other former detainees have been noted as denouncing extremism and violence.<ref name=recon/> Kettani, along with other Moroccan conservatives, distanced themselves from the Moroccan branch of [[Ansar al-Sharia (Tunisia)|Ansar al-Sharia]], refusing to lend support to the budding group.<ref>Mawassi Lahcen, [http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/reportage/2012/10/19/reportage-01 Ansar al-Sharia emerges in Morocco] by Magharebia. October 19, 2012.</ref>
Kettani's family being rooted in Morocco's traditional religious scholarship, he is an expert in both the [[Zahiri]]te and [[Maliki]]te [[Madhhab|schools]] of [[Islamic law]],<ref name=cord/> though his conservative views have been described as being at odds with the latter.<ref name=pushing/><ref name=james/>
